        <div class='o-col-oneWhole _lg-o-col-twoThirds u-mt4'>
          <p class='s-h3'>
             &lsquo;Images Pour Rien&rsquo; is my first book of photographs, comprising a year&rsquo;s worth of images of people, places, and&nbsp;presences.</p>
          <p>
            At a surface level, the book is firmly rooted in the traditions of street photography. Most of the images which make up the book have been captured in urban environments — the subjects unwitting, the action unplanned. Tropes familiar to this genre of photography (juxtapositions of subjects and of geometries, and the search for decisive moments) are employed to set the scene, encouraging a level of abstraction.
          </p>
          <p>
            Across one hundred images, presented in chronological order but without the provision of context, &lsquo;Images Pour Rien&rsquo; is a collection of photographs in search of inquisitive viewers. The title itself draws inspiration from a series of works by Samuel Beckett &mdash; an author whose prose, along with that of Polish author Bruno Schulz, have been key in shaping my interest in the creation of mysteries which remain tantalisingly unresolved.
          </p>
          <p>
            This, my first foray into publishing my photographs in book-form, is at its core an attempt to examine and question the nature of our daily realities, while engaging the viewer’s conscious and subconscious mind in the spinning of spontaneous narratives.
          </p>

